tigation into network and database metrics is recommended.", "metric_analysis_findings": "Data collection is complete. I will now proceed to analyze the Trace data to identify significant anomalies.\n\n### Findings Summary:\nThe metrics data has notable changes during the fault period, specifically in service-level response time metrics (`rrt_max` and `rrt`), as well as database I/O utilization (`io_util`). \n\n### Next Steps:\nI will analyze the provided CSV data for significant abnormalities, correlating them with node and pod relationships to identify the root cause.\nAnalyzing the provided anomaly metrics for significant changes:\n\n#### Key Observations:\n1. **`rrt_max` change observed across multiple services (currencyservice, emailservice, cartservice, shippingservice)** with high `p99_change_ratio`.\n   - Example: `currencyservice-0 rrt_max` fault P99 increased from 6729.4 to 52846.89 (1.5482 ratio).\n\n2. **Service-dependent issues in redis-cart-0**:\n   - `rrt` fault P99 increased from 930.58 to 2634.99, aligned with `pod_cpu_usage`.\n   - Redis-cart pods are mapped to Node `aiops-k8s-08`, suggesting Node-level anomalies.\n\n3. **TiDB database:**\n   - `io_util` observed for `tidb-tikv`. The median is stable (0.0 across fault period), but `p99_change_ratio` reaches a significant value of 1.1724.\n\n4. Minimal changes observed in most `node_*` metrics, suggesting service or pod-specific disruptions are likely driving the observed anomalies.\n\n#### Top Metrics with significant change ratio:\n- `currencyservice-0 rrt_max`\n- `redis-cart-0 rrt`\n- `tidb-tikv io_util`\n \nI will consolidate these into hypotheses for further investigation."}
